The paper discusses a dynamic buffer management scheme for QoS control of multimedia services in beyond 3G wireless systems, specifically in the context of the High Speed Downlink Packet Access (HSDPA) system. This involves incorporating mechanisms such as packet scheduling and HARQ in the base station, which necessitates data buffering at the air interface. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category, which deals with the design, implementation, and analysis of network protocols and architectures. Additionally, the paper focuses on multimedia services, which suggests that it could also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category, which deals with the processing, storage, and retrieval of multimedia data. The paper also discusses the impact of the buffer management scheme on end-to-end traffic performance, which could place it in the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category, which deals with the study of communication systems and their limits. Furthermore, the paper investigates the potential bottleneck introduced by data buffering at the air interface, which could place it in the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of cryptographic protocols and security mechanisms. Finally, the paper proposes a dynamic buffer management scheme, which could place it in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of distributed computing systems.
